good and the offices are so beautiful.

00:01:10.660 --> 00:01:15.790
Um, I don't want to step in that.

00:01:15.790 --> 00:01:19.479
I'd like to begin today with a story about
Bob Dylan.

00:01:19.479 --> 00:01:23.700
We heard when I walked into the room one of
his better songs playing.

00:01:23.700 --> 00:01:29.710
So, it takes place in the early summer of
1965 when Dylan was just finishing up his

00:01:29.710 --> 00:01:30.710
tour of England.

00:01:30.710 --> 00:01:35.549
It'd been a grueling few months for the singer
as he had been struggling to maintain a nonstop

00:01:35.549 --> 00:01:37.390
performance schedule.

00:01:37.390 --> 00:01:41.750
He'd first traveled across the Northeast on
a bus playing in small college towns and big

00:01:41.750 --> 00:01:42.750
city theaters.

00:01:42.750 --> 00:01:46.880
Then he crossed over the west coast to the
states and crammed in a hectic few weeks of

00:01:46.880 --> 00:01:48.909
concerts and promotion.

00:01:48.909 --> 00:01:52.850
He'd been paraded in front of the press and
asked an endless series of inane questions

00:01:52.850 --> 00:01:58.750
from, "What is the truth" to "Why is there
a cat on the cover of your last album?"

00:01:58.750 --> 00:02:04.360
When Dylan wasn't surly, he was often sarcastic,
telling journalists he collected monkey wrenches,

00:02:04.360 --> 00:02:10.920
was born in Mexico, that his songs were inspired
by chaos, watermelon and clocks.

00:02:10.920 --> 00:02:13.600
That last line almost made him smile.

00:02:13.600 --> 00:02:18.980
By the time Dylan arrived in London it was
clear the tour was taking a toll, the singer

00:02:18.980 --> 00:02:24.760
was skinny from insomnia and pills, his nails
were yellow from nicotine and his skin had

00:02:24.760 --> 00:02:27.020
a ghostly pale pallor.

00:02:27.020 --> 00:02:29.940
Joan Baez said he looked like an underfed
angel.

00:02:29.940 --> 00:02:34.270
He rare--, for the first time his solo shows
felt formulaic as if he were singing the lines

00:02:34.270 --> 00:02:35.270
of someone else.

00:02:35.270 --> 00:02:39.110
He rarely acknowledged the audience or paused
between songs, he seemed to be in a hurry

00:02:39.110 --> 00:02:41.389
to get off stage.

00:02:41.389 --> 00:02:44.329
Before long, it all became too much.

00:02:44.329 --> 00:02:48.260
While touring in England Dylan decided that
he was leading an impossible life.

00:02:48.260 --> 00:02:52.800
The only talent he cared about, his ceaseless
creativity was being ruined by fame.

00:02:52.800 --> 00:02:56.769
The breaking point probably came after a brief
vacation in Portugal where Dylan came down

00:02:56.769 --> 00:02:58.620
with a vicious case of food poisoning.

00:02:58.620 --> 00:03:02.990
The illness forced him to stay in bed for
a week, giving the singer a rare chance to

00:03:02.990 --> 00:03:03.990
reflect.

00:03:03.990 --> 00:03:08.269
"I realized I was very drained" Dylan would
later say, "I was playing a lot of songs I

00:03:08.269 --> 00:03:09.269
didn't want to play.

00:03:09.269 --> 00:03:11.120
I was singing words I didn't really want to
sing.

00:03:11.120 --> 00:03:15.470
It's very tiring having other people tell
you how much they dig you if you yourself

00:03:15.470 --> 00:03:17.040
don't dig you."

00:03:17.040 --> 00:03:18.910
The last shows were in London.

00:03:18.910 --> 00:03:23.020
It was here that Dylan told his manager that
he was quitting the music business.

00:03:23.020 --> 00:03:25.060
He was finished with singing and song writing.

00:03:25.060 --> 00:03:29.530
He was gonna move to a tiny cabin in Woodstock,
New York.

00:03:29.530 --> 00:03:34.200
Although Dylan had become a pop icon, the
prophetic poet of his generation, he was ready

00:03:34.200 --> 00:03:35.860
to renounce it all.

00:03:35.860 --> 00:03:38.620
He just wanted to be left alone.

00:03:38.620 --> 00:03:39.940
Dylan wasn't bluffing.

00:03:39.940 --> 00:03:44.419
As promised he returned from his British tour
and rode his Triumph motorcycle straight out

00:03:44.419 --> 00:03:48.420
of New York City; he didn't even bring his
guitar.

00:03:48.420 --> 00:03:50.840
Of course our story doesn't end here.

00:03:50.840 --> 00:03:53.770
Bob Dylan did not retire in 1965.

00:03:53.770 --> 00:03:58.990
After a few relaxing days in Woodstock, just
when he was most determined to stop creating

00:03:58.990 --> 00:04:01.660
music, he was overcome with the familiar feeling.

00:04:01.660 --> 00:04:04.290
"It's hard thing to describe," Dylan would
later remember.

00:04:04.290 --> 00:04:07.100
"It's just a sense that you've got something
to say."

00:04:07.100 --> 00:04:11.450
So Dylan did the only thing he knew how to
do, he grabbed a pencil and pad of paper and

00:04:11.450 --> 00:04:13.299
started to scribble.

00:04:13.299 --> 00:04:16.650
Once Dylan began his hand didn't stop for
the next several hours.

00:04:16.650 --> 00:04:21.040
"I found myself writing this song, this story,
this long piece of vomit.

00:04:21.040 --> 00:04:26.290
20 pages long," Dylan said, "I'd never written
anything like that before and it suddenly

00:04:26.290 --> 00:04:28.860
came to me that this is what I should do."

00:04:28.860 --> 00:04:31.790
Vomit is the essential word here.

00:04:31.790 --> 00:04:37.040
Dylan is describing with characteristic vividness,
the uncontrollable rush of creative insight,

00:04:37.040 --> 00:04:40.400
that flow of associations that can't be held
back.

00:04:40.400 --> 00:04:44.670
"I don't know where my songs come from," Dylan
said, "It's like a ghost is writing the song.

00:04:44.670 --> 00:04:49.460
It gives you the song and it goes away, you
don't know what it means."

00:04:49.460 --> 00:04:55.090
In retrospect, we can see that this frantic
composition, these words written by the ghost

00:04:55.090 --> 00:05:00.070
in Woodstock allowed Dylan to fully express
for the very first time the full diversity

00:05:00.070 --> 00:05:01.180
of his influences.

00:05:01.180 --> 00:05:06.000
In his cryptic lyrics, we can hear his mental
blender at work as he mixes together scraps

00:05:06.000 --> 00:05:10.430
of Blake, Fellini, Woody Guthrie and Robert
Johnson.

00:05:10.430 --> 00:05:15.260
Songs are modernist and pre modern, avant
garde and country western.

00:05:15.260 --> 00:05:21.250
What Dylan did, and this is why he's Bob Dylan,
is find the strange thread connecting these

00:05:21.250 --> 00:05:22.960
different voices.

00:05:22.960 --> 00:05:27.040
In those first minutes of writing, he found
a way to make something new out of this incongruous

00:05:27.040 --> 00:05:31.790
list of influences, drawing them together
into a catchy song.

00:05:31.790 --> 00:05:35.310
When Dylan gets to the chorus and he knows
this is the chorus as soon as he commits it

00:05:35.310 --> 00:05:39.350
to paper, the visceral power of his words
becomes obvious.

00:05:39.350 --> 00:05:42.420
"How does it feel without a home?

00:05:42.420 --> 00:05:46.240
Like a complete unknown, like a rolling stone."

00:05:46.240 --> 00:05:52.300
The following week, on June 15th, 1965, Dylan
would bring the sheaf of papers into the cramped

00:05:52.300 --> 00:05:56.530
space of Studio A Columbia records in New
York City.

00:05:56.530 --> 00:06:02.670
After just 4 takes, the musician's only beginning
to learn their parts, "Like a Rolling Stone"

00:06:02.670 --> 00:06:03.840
was cut on acetate.

00:06:03.840 --> 00:06:10.330
Those 6 minutes of raw music would revolutionize
rock and roll.

00:06:10.330 --> 00:06:16.390
The story of "Like a Rolling Stone," the reason
I'm talking about Bob Dylan today, is because

00:06:16.390 --> 00:06:18.830
it's a story about a moment of insight.

00:06:18.830 --> 00:06:24.480
At times, such stories can feel like romantic
clichés, the sort of make believe breakthroughs

00:06:24.480 --> 00:06:28.650
that happened to Archimedes in the bathtub
and Newton under the apple tree.

00:06:28.650 --> 00:06:32.610
And yet, insights do happen, they are a genuine
mental event.

00:06:32.610 --> 00:06:37.820
They really are responsible for the theory
of gravity and "Like a Rolling Stone."

00:06:37.820 --> 00:06:41.220
In recent years, cognitive psychologists and
neuroscientists made some interesting progress

00:06:41.220 --> 00:06:46.060
trying to understand these most mysterious
of mental moments in terms that there are

00:06:46.060 --> 00:06:48.330
two defining features to moments of insight.

00:06:48.330 --> 00:06:52.639
The first defining feature is the answer just
arrives out of the blue, arrives when we least

00:06:52.639 --> 00:06:53.639
expect it.

00:06:53.639 --> 00:06:58.790
So we wrote our best song, our most influential
song after we quit the singing and song writing

00:06:58.790 --> 00:06:59.790
business.

00:06:59.790 --> 00:07:02.630
The second defining feature is as soon as
the answer arrives, as soon as we write those

00:07:02.630 --> 00:07:05.900
words down, we know this is the answer we've
been searching for.

00:07:05.900 --> 00:07:09.170
That this is the solution we need.

00:07:09.170 --> 00:07:13.290
It comes attached with this feeling of certainty,
it seems like a revelation.

00:07:13.290 --> 00:07:16.570
So those are the two defining features of
moments of insight.

00:07:16.570 --> 00:07:21.020
And at first glance, it's not quite clear
how one can scientifically study such things

00:07:21.020 --> 00:07:26.630
cause you can't just put undergraduates in
a brain scanner, fMRI machine and say, "Have

00:07:26.630 --> 00:07:28.130
an epiphany we're ready for you."

00:07:28.130 --> 00:07:30.590
[Laughter]
&gt;&gt;Jonah Lehrer: That'd be very inefficient.

00:07:30.590 --> 00:07:34.800
So, instead, what scientists had to do is
come up with a way to generate lots of moments

00:07:34.800 --> 00:07:35.910
of insight on the fly.

00:07:35.910 --> 00:07:40.370
And I'm talking today, primarily, about the
research of Mark Beeman at Northwestern and

00:07:40.370 --> 00:07:42.870
John Kounios at Drexel University.

00:07:42.870 --> 00:07:47.790
And they came up with a set of word problems
called compound remote associate problems.

00:07:47.790 --> 00:07:50.470
The acronym has been unfortunate, C-R-A-P.

00:07:50.470 --> 00:07:53.520
But they generated lots of moments of insight.

00:07:53.520 --> 00:07:56.910
So the problems go like this, I'm gonna give
you three words, you have to find a fourth

00:07:56.910 --> 00:07:59.830
word that can form a compound word with these
three words.

00:07:59.830 --> 00:08:02.120
So we'll do the first one together.

00:08:02.120 --> 00:08:10.090
The three words are pine, crab and sauce,
the fourth word in this case is apple; pineapple,

00:08:10.090 --> 00:08:11.770
crab apple, applesauce.

00:08:11.770 --> 00:08:13.170
Here's one for you guys.

00:08:13.170 --> 00:08:17.850
The three words are age, mile and sand.

00:08:17.850 --> 00:08:21.710
What's the fourth word that can form a compound
word with age, mile and sand?

00:08:21.710 --> 00:08:23.449
&gt;&gt;male audience member: stone.

00:08:23.449 --> 00:08:27.940
&gt;&gt;Jonah Lehrer: An answer that quick is most
certainly a moment of insight.

00:08:27.940 --> 00:08:30.949
The answer is stone, stone age, milestone
and sandstone.

00:08:30.949 --> 00:08:34.899
So the first thing Beeman and Kounios discovered
when they gave people these compound remote

00:08:34.899 --> 00:08:39.089
associate problems inside an fMRI machine
is that in the seconds before the insight

00:08:39.089 --> 00:08:44.630
appeared an obscure part of the brain called
the anterior superior temporal gyrus in the

00:08:44.630 --> 00:08:48.441
back of the right hemisphere just behind your
ear, showed a sharp spike in activity.

00:08:48.441 --> 00:08:50.540
It's a brain area nobody knows too much about.

00:08:50.540 --> 00:08:55.029
It's been previously associated with things
like the processing of jokes and the interpretation

00:08:55.029 --> 00:08:56.029
of metaphors.

00:08:56.029 --> 00:08:58.790
And this begins to make a little sense, right?

00:08:58.790 --> 00:09:03.511
When Romeo says that Juliet is the sun, we
know he's not saying that Juliet is a big

00:09:03.511 --> 00:09:07.060
flaming ball of plasma gas, we realize he's
trafficking metaphor.

00:09:07.060 --> 00:09:11.390
And how we make sense of that metaphor is
by looking past all the surface dissimilarities.

00:09:11.390 --> 00:09:15.820
The fact that Juliet and suns have literally
nothing in common and, instead, searching

00:09:15.820 --> 00:09:19.180
for the underlying themes it actually shares.

00:09:19.180 --> 00:09:24.360
We're able to realize that Romeo is saying
Juliet lights up his world the way the sun

00:09:24.360 --> 00:09:25.850
lights up ours.

00:09:25.850 --> 00:09:30.120
Now a similar process is unfolding when you
need to make sense of pine, crab and sauce.

00:09:30.120 --> 00:09:33.500
Those aren't three words that go together
very frequently, you've probably never used

00:09:33.500 --> 00:09:38.290
them in a sentence before, yet this one brain
area, the anterior superior temporal gyrus,

00:09:38.290 --> 00:09:42.700
seems to be particularly good at finding the
thin thread that binds them together.

00:09:42.700 --> 00:09:43.700
[Laughter]

00:09:43.700 --> 00:09:46.830
&gt;&gt;male offstage: they're at the other office

00:09:46.830 --> 00:09:48.690
&gt;&gt;Jonah Lehrer: Oh!

00:09:48.690 --> 00:09:53.029
[Laughter]
&gt;&gt;Jonah Lehrer: 21st century is amazing.

00:09:53.029 --> 00:09:55.920
[Laughter]
&gt;&gt;Jonah Lehrer: So it's able to find the one

00:09:55.920 --> 00:09:58.190
other word that binds them all together

00:09:58.190 --> 00:09:59.190
[Laughter]

00:09:59.190 --> 00:10:01.660
&gt;&gt;Jonah Lehrer: Oh no, our friends, what happened?

00:10:01.660 --> 00:10:03.200
Oh they're still happening.

00:10:03.200 --> 00:10:04.750
Oh, that's too bad.

00:10:04.750 --> 00:10:07.380
[Laughter]
&gt;&gt;Jonah Lehrer: So it's able to find the one

00:10:07.380 --> 00:10:09.060
other word that binds them all together.

00:10:09.060 --> 00:10:13.350
Now when you need a moment of insight, when
you're stuck and stumped, when you don't know

00:10:13.350 --> 00:10:17.930
what to do next, when you've just reached
that block, chances are you also need to draw

00:10:17.930 --> 00:10:20.880
together a set of distantly related ideas.

00:10:20.880 --> 00:10:24.740
If the connections were on the surface, if
they were literal, if they were obvious, you

00:10:24.740 --> 00:10:25.740
would have found them already.

00:10:25.740 --> 00:10:29.430
The fact that you need an epiphany suggests
that they're hidden and you need to draw together

00:10:29.430 --> 00:10:30.600
a set of remote associations.

00:10:30.600 --> 00:10:36.540
And that's what this one brain are, the anterior
superior temporal gyrus, seems to be so good

00:10:36.540 --> 00:10:37.540
at.

00:10:37.540 --> 00:10:40.850
Just the first that Beeman and Kounios discovered,
second is found to be a bit more interesting.

00:10:40.850 --> 00:10:45.070
This they discovered when they hooked people
up to an EEG, it's like wearing a big bulky

00:10:45.070 --> 00:10:49.610
shower cap that measures the waves of electricity
pouring out of your head.

00:10:49.610 --> 00:10:54.529
What they discovered is they could predict
up to 8 seconds in advance whether or not

00:10:54.529 --> 00:10:56.399
someone was gonna have a moment of insight.

00:10:56.399 --> 00:10:58.310
Now, just think how spooky this is.

00:10:58.310 --> 00:10:59.850
They could look at your brain waves.

00:10:59.850 --> 00:11:04.490
They could say, "Sorry, buddy, you could sit
here all day trying to solve these word problems

00:11:04.490 --> 00:11:06.050
and you would get nowhere.

00:11:06.050 --> 00:11:08.589
You're wasting your time, go home."

00:11:08.589 --> 00:11:12.440
Or they could say, "You know what, in about
7 and a half seconds you're gonna have an

00:11:12.440 --> 00:11:15.080
epiphany so brace yourself."

00:11:15.080 --> 00:11:19.110
The question, of course, of what this predictive
signal is, turns out to be something called

00:11:19.110 --> 00:11:20.460
alpha waves.

00:11:20.460 --> 00:11:23.740
Like most things in the mind, alpha waves
are pretty mysterious but they are closely

00:11:23.740 --> 00:11:25.390
associated with states of relaxation.

00:11:25.390 --> 00:11:29.839
So, things that lead to the production of
lots of alpha waves are things like taking

00:11:29.839 --> 00:11:36.520
a walk on the beach, having a beer on the
couch, taking a long hot shower, playing foosball,

00:11:36.520 --> 00:11:40.830
whatever it is that gets you to stop thinking
about those problems at work that you just

00:11:40.830 --> 00:11:45.800
can't solve, that puts your mind at ease,
that allows you to daydream without constantly

00:11:45.800 --> 00:11:50.700
being interrupted, that's probably a place
that's gonna generate lots of alpha waves.

00:11:50.700 --> 00:11:54.290
Now, the reason these states of relaxation
are so important, Beeman and Kounios argue,

00:11:54.290 --> 00:11:58.870
is when we're not relaxed, when we're focused,
when we're juiced on caffeine, when we're

00:11:58.870 --> 00:12:03.180
chained to our desk, staring at our computer
screen, working late at the office, that's

00:12:03.180 --> 00:12:04.180
where our attention is.

00:12:04.180 --> 00:12:08.070
It's out in the world, we are consumed by
the noise, we are thinking about pine, crab

00:12:08.070 --> 00:12:09.070
and sauce.

00:12:09.070 --> 00:12:13.490
Pine, crab and sauce and inspire a wrong answer,
a common wrong answer for pine, crab and sauce

00:12:13.490 --> 00:12:16.480
is tree, that we just can't get past.

00:12:16.480 --> 00:12:20.970
And so we're frustrated, we're stuck, we're
making no progress.

00:12:20.970 --> 00:12:27.500
That's why [inaudible] were in the warm shower,
shampooing our hair, unable to check our email,

00:12:27.500 --> 00:12:31.000
that at long last we're able to turn the spot
light of attention inwards and that's when

00:12:31.000 --> 00:12:34.850
we're able to hear that quite voice coming
from the back of our head telling us, "the

00:12:34.850 --> 00:12:37.640
answer is apple", "the answer is apple."

00:12:37.640 --> 00:12:42.770
Maybe that voice has been there for hours
or days or weeks, we just haven't taken a

00:12:42.770 --> 00:12:43.770
moment to listen.

00:12:43.770 --> 00:12:48.970
Beeman and Kounios tell this wonderful story
about this trained Tibetan Buddhist monk who,

00:12:48.970 --> 00:12:53.790
this guy meditates 12 hours a day, so he's
got exquisite control over the spotlight of

00:12:53.790 --> 00:12:57.750
his attention, and at first, he thought the
way to solve these compound association problems

00:12:57.750 --> 00:12:58.750
was to stay very focused.

00:12:58.750 --> 00:13:02.420
He'd think about pine, crab and sauce and
of course that's the wrong approach, so he

00:13:02.420 --> 00:13:03.420
went 0 for 30.

00:13:03.420 --> 00:13:07.290
Normally he's prompted about a twenty percent
success rate, but he was going 0 for 30 cause

00:13:07.290 --> 00:13:08.690
he was just really, really focused.

00:13:08.690 --> 00:13:12.440
And then at a certain point he realized, "You
know, I'm using the wrong strategy, maybe

00:13:12.440 --> 00:13:13.620
I should switch it up."

00:13:13.620 --> 00:13:15.690
And because he's a trained mediator he's able
to-

00:13:15.690 --> 00:13:17.550
[Snapping]
&gt;&gt;Jonah Lehrer: increase his alpha waves like

00:13:17.550 --> 00:13:18.732
that, on a dime.

00:13:18.732 --> 00:13:24.010
And they watch this abrupt spike in his brain
waves and then he became an insight machine.

00:13:24.010 --> 00:13:28.740
He solved 25 in a row, a streak they had never
seen before or since.

00:13:28.740 --> 00:13:31.850
That's because he was focused on not being
focused.

00:13:31.850 --> 00:13:34.480
Now there is something counterintuitive about
this work, right?

00:13:34.480 --> 00:13:40.621
I think we all assume on giving a hard problem
that what we should do is work harder, pay

00:13:40.621 --> 00:13:45.471
more attention to it, chug that Red Bull,
snort that Ritalin, do whatever it is that

00:13:45.471 --> 00:13:46.471
we need to do
[Laughter]

00:13:46.471 --> 00:13:48.920
&gt;&gt;Jonah Lehrer: to maintain our attention.

00:13:48.920 --> 00:13:53.030
But this research suggests that's the exact
wrong thing to do.

00:13:53.030 --> 00:13:56.180
That we will be focused but we will be focused
