Monte canning factory outside of Oakland.

00:27:33.320 --> 00:27:37.119
But Jobs realized, you know what, it's not
enough to just put people in the same building,

00:27:37.119 --> 00:27:39.389
we need to force them to mix and mingle.

00:27:39.389 --> 00:27:43.042
So he carved out this big atrium and he put
everything important in the atrium, he put

00:27:43.042 --> 00:27:46.909
the mailboxes there and the gift store there
and the cafeteria there and the coffee shop

00:27:46.909 --> 00:27:47.909
there.

00:27:47.909 --> 00:27:50.029
And he realized, you know what, even that's
not enough cause you can build people a gleaming

00:27:50.029 --> 00:27:53.750
cafeteria and serve delicious food but the
animators would still have lunch with the

00:27:53.750 --> 00:27:57.049
animators, computer scientists would still
have snacks with computer scientists and so

00:27:57.049 --> 00:27:58.049
on.

00:27:58.049 --> 00:28:01.919
So then in one of his moments of insight,
he decided that there would only be two bathrooms

00:28:01.919 --> 00:28:03.850
in the entire Pixar Studios
[Laughter]

00:28:03.850 --> 00:28:05.700
&gt;&gt;Jonah Lehrer: And he put those in the atrium.

00:28:05.700 --> 00:28:10.049
So there's one place we all have to go every
single day, it's the bathroom.

00:28:10.049 --> 00:28:13.850
And at first the people at Pixar thought this
was the worst idea ever, right, it's a huge

00:28:13.850 --> 00:28:18.120
factory, it's a quarter mile long nearly,
so if you're at the wrong end of the building,

00:28:18.120 --> 00:28:21.539
it can be a long walk to the bathroom.

00:28:21.539 --> 00:28:25.009
But now when you spend time at Pixar you hear
again and again these stories of these bathroom

00:28:25.009 --> 00:28:26.009
epiphanies.

00:28:26.009 --> 00:28:30.909
The great conversation they had while washing
their hands or that serendipitous chat they

00:28:30.909 --> 00:28:33.710
had in the hallway on the way to the bathroom.

00:28:33.710 --> 00:28:39.399
That, as Jobs once put it, "Creativity is
just connecting things and most of those connections

00:28:39.399 --> 00:28:40.710
come from other people."

00:28:40.710 --> 00:28:44.059
Now, there's some neat empirical proof to
this concept.

00:28:44.059 --> 00:28:46.059
This comes from the work of Isaac Kohane at
Harvard.

00:28:46.059 --> 00:28:48.059
[Coughing]
&gt;&gt;Jonah Lehrer: He analyzed 20 thousand papers

00:28:48.059 --> 00:28:49.570
produced by Harvard researchers.

00:28:49.570 --> 00:28:54.049
This took him several years and a small army
of undergrads because he had to map out the

00:28:54.049 --> 00:28:58.769
physical location of every single Harvard
coauthor down to the nearest meter.

00:28:58.769 --> 00:29:04.149
But what he discovered is that physical location,
what he calls collocation, that it matters,

00:29:04.149 --> 00:29:05.639
it matters a lot.

00:29:05.639 --> 00:29:09.450
That papers produced when scientists were
within 10 meters of each other, which meant

00:29:09.450 --> 00:29:12.940
they shared the same water cooler, the same
coffee room and the same bathroom, that those

00:29:12.940 --> 00:29:17.190
papers were 3 times more likely to be highly
cited than papers produced when scientists

00:29:17.190 --> 00:29:19.129
were a kilometer or more apart.

00:29:19.129 --> 00:29:24.259
The lesson here is that even in this age of
wonderful technologies, our most important

00:29:24.259 --> 00:29:27.049
ideas often don't arrive on a screen.

00:29:27.049 --> 00:29:32.700
Rather they emerge from idle conversation,
from too many people sharing the same space.

00:29:32.700 --> 00:29:35.679
Now, personally, I find this surprising.

00:29:35.679 --> 00:29:41.090
I mean, you go back ten years and you hear
people making very convincing arguments, futurists

00:29:41.090 --> 00:29:45.049
making these convincing arguments, that it's
the death of geography.

00:29:45.049 --> 00:29:48.799
We live in an age where geography and physical
space are gonna become obsolete.

00:29:48.799 --> 00:29:50.519
Why should we all move to London?

00:29:50.519 --> 00:29:55.969
Why should we cram ourselves into these expensive,
overcrowded, smelly, crime ridden places full

00:29:55.969 --> 00:29:58.599
of traffic and too many strangers?

00:29:58.599 --> 00:30:00.549
What's the possible value of that?

00:30:00.549 --> 00:30:04.419
Why should we even come to an office, why
not just sit at home in our pajamas in the

00:30:04.419 --> 00:30:06.109
suburbs and telecommute?

00:30:06.109 --> 00:30:07.109
It's so much easier.

00:30:07.109 --> 00:30:08.629
It's so much more efficient.

00:30:08.629 --> 00:30:11.100
Needless to say, that hasn't happened.

00:30:11.100 --> 00:30:12.929
If anything, the opposite has happened.

00:30:12.929 --> 00:30:16.119
Cities are more valuable than ever before,
more and more people are moving to cities.

00:30:16.119 --> 00:30:19.309
Urbanization is the great theme of the 21st
century.

00:30:19.309 --> 00:30:22.639
That in the next 100 years more people will
move to cities than have moved to cities in

00:30:22.639 --> 00:30:24.039
all of human history.

00:30:24.039 --> 00:30:26.899
So this is a huge and growing trend.

00:30:26.899 --> 00:30:32.059
One of my favorite factoids is that since
the invention of Skype, attendance at business

00:30:32.059 --> 00:30:34.460
conferences has nearly doubled.

00:30:34.460 --> 00:30:36.719
That even though we live in this age that,
in theory, we could sit at home and get the

00:30:36.719 --> 00:30:41.649
same content just on a screen, we know that
it's important to come together in person,

00:30:41.649 --> 00:30:45.369
to rub up against strangers, to have those
random chats.

00:30:45.369 --> 00:30:50.320
And I don't mean this is any way to dismiss
the importance of these new tools, you know,

00:30:50.320 --> 00:30:53.190
to dismiss the importance of all these wonderful
gadgets.

00:30:53.190 --> 00:30:58.009
To be able to search for anything on Google
on this phone in my pocket, that is an amazing

00:30:58.009 --> 00:30:59.009
thing.

00:30:59.009 --> 00:31:03.309
But these tools, they tend to make our lives
more efficient, they make it so much easier

00:31:03.309 --> 00:31:04.609
to find stuff.

00:31:04.609 --> 00:31:07.099
But creativity, when you look at it, it's
not really about efficiency.

00:31:07.099 --> 00:31:08.099
It's about serendipity.

00:31:08.099 --> 00:31:11.729
It's about encountering that information you
didn't even know to look for, about bumping

00:31:11.729 --> 00:31:17.929
into that person you didn't even know to meet,
that, even in the 21st century, it is still

00:31:17.929 --> 00:31:22.399
the human friction that makes the sparks.

00:31:22.399 --> 00:31:27.999
The last idea I'd like to end with is a provocative
one and I think it's especially provocative

00:31:27.999 --> 00:31:31.649
for a company like Google with such an incredibly
rich history of innovation.

00:31:31.649 --> 00:31:37.100
And it speaks, I think, to the difficulty
of maintaining this pace of creativity.

00:31:37.100 --> 00:31:43.729
In fact, it suggests that many of the things
typical companies do with the best of intentions

00:31:43.729 --> 00:31:47.710
to make their workers more creative, actually
get in the way.

00:31:47.710 --> 00:31:51.639
This is best demonstrated by the work of Geoffrey
West, he's a theoretical physicist at the

00:31:51.639 --> 00:31:53.389
Santa Fe Institute.

00:31:53.389 --> 00:31:56.799
He studies cities and gathers vast tracks
of data from governments from all across the

00:31:56.799 --> 00:32:01.690
world trying to understand what makes cities
tick and why some cities tick better than

00:32:01.690 --> 00:32:02.690
others.

00:32:02.690 --> 00:32:05.769
He's done all sorts of peculiar correlations.

00:32:05.769 --> 00:32:11.669
One of my favorites is that when you're trying
to find the most predictive variable of patents

00:32:11.669 --> 00:32:16.059
per capita in a given metropolis, it turns
out to be the walking speed of pedestrians.

00:32:16.059 --> 00:32:21.159
First of all, who knew the census bureau in
the states collected data on the walking speed

00:32:21.159 --> 00:32:22.159
of pedestrians.

00:32:22.159 --> 00:32:25.890
But, that's bizarre enough, but nobody knows
what to make of this correlation.

00:32:25.890 --> 00:32:30.059
It could be a random accident, it could be
just a statistical fluke, but West argues

00:32:30.059 --> 00:32:31.110
that it begins to make sense.

00:32:31.110 --> 00:32:36.830
The function of a city is to foster those
bumps, to get people to just have those random

00:32:36.830 --> 00:32:41.970
interactions while waiting in line for a latte,
on the sidewalk, so in a sense people are

00:32:41.970 --> 00:32:42.970
particles.

00:32:42.970 --> 00:32:44.309
You can model urban dwellers as particles.

00:32:44.309 --> 00:32:48.519
And if you increase the velocity of those
particle, you make those pedestrians walk

00:32:48.519 --> 00:32:52.559
just a bit faster, you get more bumps and
eventually those bumps add up and you get

00:32:52.559 --> 00:32:53.690
a new patent.

00:32:53.690 --> 00:32:58.299
But, West makes this very interesting comparison
between cities and companies.

00:32:58.299 --> 00:33:02.710
He points out that from a certain perspective,
cities and companies look quite similar, right?

00:33:02.710 --> 00:33:08.639
They're both big clusters of people in a fixed
physical space, lots of infrastructure, yet

00:33:08.639 --> 00:33:11.989
cities and companies exhibit one very interesting
difference.

00:33:11.989 --> 00:33:18.159
That cities, this form of social organization
we call cities, they never die.

00:33:18.159 --> 00:33:19.779
They are immortal.

00:33:19.779 --> 00:33:21.071
You can nuke a city, comes back.

00:33:21.071 --> 00:33:23.250
You can flood a city, bounces back.

00:33:23.250 --> 00:33:28.620
You can have a devastating earthquake, burn
the city to the ground and we still have San

00:33:28.620 --> 00:33:29.629
Francisco.

00:33:29.629 --> 00:33:32.429
Companies, on the other hand, die all the
time.

00:33:32.429 --> 00:33:34.419
They are incredibly fragile.

00:33:34.419 --> 00:33:40.080
Fortune 100 firms, these huge multinational
firms, their average lifespan is 45 years.

00:33:40.080 --> 00:33:43.299
Only two companies in the original Dow Jones
index are still around.

00:33:43.299 --> 00:33:48.039
More than 25 percent of Fortune 500 firms
die every decade.

00:33:48.039 --> 00:33:53.779
So West wanted to understand, what's the difference,
why are cities immortal, resilient and perdurable?

00:33:53.779 --> 00:33:56.339
Why are companies so fragile and fleeting?

00:33:56.339 --> 00:34:01.309
Well, by analyzing lots and lots of data he
found an interesting difference and the difference

00:34:01.309 --> 00:34:02.940
is this.

00:34:02.940 --> 00:34:07.950
As cities get bigger everyone in that city
becomes more productive, by every metric we

00:34:07.950 --> 00:34:11.901
have, they're gonna look better, they're gonna
make more money, invent more patents, invent

00:34:11.901 --> 00:34:13.090
more trademarks and so on.

00:34:13.090 --> 00:34:15.520
This is the trend, in fact, that's making
our cities bigger.

00:34:15.520 --> 00:34:19.380
This is what's driving urbanization; it's
called superlinear scaling.

00:34:19.380 --> 00:34:23.850
So urban productivity looks like this, like
a roller coaster taking off into the sky.

00:34:23.850 --> 00:34:29.310
This is why West calls cities the most important
invention in the history of human civilization,

00:34:29.310 --> 00:34:31.550
the idea that's unleashed so many of our ideas.

00:34:31.550 --> 00:34:34.940
You get this social multiplier effect in the
cities.

00:34:34.940 --> 00:34:37.929
Companies, on the other hand, look very different.

00:34:37.929 --> 00:34:42.270
As a company gets bigger, everyone in that
company becomes less productive.

00:34:42.270 --> 00:34:46.840
They bring in less profit per employee, fewer
patents per employee, fewer trademarks and

00:34:46.840 --> 00:34:47.840
so on.

00:34:47.840 --> 00:34:49.080
This is called sublinear scaling.

00:34:49.080 --> 00:34:53.920
So companies look like this and over time
this becomes a dangerous trend, right, because

00:34:53.920 --> 00:34:58.290
Wall Street there's all this pressure to keep
on getting bigger to grow the bottom lines.

00:34:58.290 --> 00:34:59.290
That's what companies do.

00:34:59.290 --> 00:35:03.650
But that means you've got expanded bureaucracy,
expanded fixed cost, but you're no longer

00:35:03.650 --> 00:35:05.250
innovating at the same rate.

00:35:05.250 --> 00:35:08.860
So you become more reliant on your old ideas
for your new ideas, you have an expense of

00:35:08.860 --> 00:35:10.500
expensive acquisitions.

00:35:10.500 --> 00:35:14.570
But eventually, those old ideas are no longer
useful, those acquisitions don't pan out and

00:35:14.570 --> 00:35:16.910
that's when you go belly up.

00:35:16.910 --> 00:35:21.060
Now what causes the difference, why are cities
superlinear and companies are sublinear?

00:35:21.060 --> 00:35:23.900
West argues it's because companies get in
the way.

00:35:23.900 --> 00:35:27.680
When you think about a city, the magic of
a city is no one's in charge.

00:35:27.680 --> 00:35:31.520
It's a freewheeling chaotic place and a mayor's
a pretty powerless figure.

00:35:31.520 --> 00:35:34.680
He can't tell you where to live or who to
talk to or what to work on.

00:35:34.680 --> 00:35:39.140
It's just a bunch of particles, a bunch of
strangers going about their business, bumping

00:35:39.140 --> 00:35:40.140
into each other.

00:35:40.140 --> 00:35:45.310
That because cities don't try to maximize
creativity, that's exactly what they end up

00:35:45.310 --> 00:35:46.310
doing.

00:35:46.310 --> 00:35:48.360
Companies, on the other hand, try to micromanage
the process.

00:35:48.360 --> 00:35:52.140
So, they tell us who to talk to, they tell
us what to work on, you know, brainstorm,

00:35:52.140 --> 00:35:56.200
they tell us don't drink a beer in the afternoon,
focus, focus, focus.

00:35:56.200 --> 00:36:01.310
They stifle horizontal interactions becoming
these very vertical places; they silo knowledge

00:36:01.310 --> 00:36:02.460
and so on.

00:36:02.460 --> 00:36:07.200
And in all these things, many of which are
done with the best of intentions, they actually

00:36:07.200 --> 00:36:10.360
get in the way, they hold us back.

00:36:10.360 --> 00:36:17.130
So West's advice is simple, when in doubt
imitate the city.

00:36:17.130 --> 00:36:22.700
In closing, the imagination has always seemed
like a magic trick of matter which is probably

00:36:22.700 --> 00:36:25.840
why we've always blamed our best ideas on
the muses.

00:36:25.840 --> 00:36:30.030
The good news, that by finally understanding
where our new ideas come from, we can hopefully

00:36:30.030 --> 00:36:31.930
have a few more of them.

00:36:31.930 --> 00:36:35.960
The science of creativity can make us just
a little bit more creative.

00:36:35.960 --> 00:36:38.000
But we must also be honest.

00:36:38.000 --> 00:36:43.090
The creative process will never be easy no
matter how much we know about neurons or cities.

00:36:43.090 --> 00:36:47.111
The science of the imagination doesn't fit
neatly on a Power Point slide and it can't

00:36:47.111 --> 00:36:49.210
be summarized in a subtitle.

00:36:49.210 --> 00:36:53.560
If creativity were that easy, Picasso wouldn't
be so famous and it wouldn't require so much

00:36:53.560 --> 00:36:54.560
grit.

00:36:54.560 --> 00:36:59.970
It's about all of the clever studies and rigorous
experiments our most essential talent remains

00:36:59.970 --> 00:37:01.300
our most mysterious.

00:37:01.300 --> 00:37:06.720
The mystery is this; although the imagination
is inspired by the everyday world, by its

00:37:06.720 --> 00:37:11.760
flaws and its beauties, we are able to see
beyond our sources to imagine things that

00:37:11.760 --> 00:37:13.970
only exist in the mind.

00:37:13.970 --> 00:37:17.920
There was nothing, now there is something,
it's almost like magic.

00:37:17.920 --> 00:37:21.910
Thank you all so much for having me at Google
and thank you so much for listening today.

00:37:21.910 --> 00:37:26.360
I think we've got some time for Q and A, so
that's my favorite part, so please have at

00:37:26.360 --> 00:37:28.590
it.

00:37:28.590 --> 00:37:30.820
[Applause]

00:37:30.820 --> 00:37:41.501
&gt;&gt;male #1: Thank you so much for that, so
it's hard to choose whether I should ask a

00:37:41.501 --> 00:37:46.000
question on the individual side or the organizational
side; I'll go with the individual side.

00:37:46.000 --> 00:37:52.190
Which is, when you think about alpha waves
and more about the pervasiveness of technology,

00:37:52.190 --> 00:37:57.660
do you think those moments where we can actually
detach have now gone away because we always

00:37:57.660 --> 00:38:01.590
have a phone in our pocket, a tablet and access
to these things?

00:38:01.590 --> 00:38:04.160
Or is our only sanctum the shower now?

00:38:04.160 --> 00:38:08.810
&gt;&gt;Jonah Lehrer: I mean, it's a really interesting
question and I always try to resist the urge

00:38:08.810 --> 00:38:11.170
to speculate on the forwarding effects of
technology.

00:38:11.170 --> 00:38:14.760
I think it's so easy to be scared by it or
think it's gonna change everything.

00:38:14.760 --> 00:38:17.580
You know, Google's either making us stupid
or it's the salvation.

00:38:17.580 --> 00:38:22.890
And I think it's complicated, I mean, like
I said, these tools are amazing.

00:38:22.890 --> 00:38:26.160
They're allowing us to connect and expose
ourselves to information we never could have

00:38:26.160 --> 00:38:27.500
had before.

00:38:27.500 --> 00:38:28.900
I think they fuel our curiosity.

00:38:28.900 --> 00:38:34.600
But, in my own life, what I can say is that
I have noticed that now when I'm bored, the

00:38:34.600 --> 00:38:38.500
first thing I do, no matter where I am, is
I get out my phone and I check my email, I

00:38:38.500 --> 00:38:43.560
check Twitter, I check, you know, I go to
Google News, whatever it is.

00:38:43.560 --> 00:38:46.340
So I'm always interrupting my daydreams.

00:38:46.340 --> 00:38:51.720
And that worries me simply because we've learned
in the last few years that day dreaming, this

00:38:51.720 --> 00:38:55.800
mental state we've always told our kids not
to practice, we've assumed it's like this

00:38:55.800 --> 00:38:57.960
form of thinking when we don't want to think
at all.

00:38:57.960 --> 00:39:01.590
It turns out to be incredibly useful, that
your brain consumes more energy while day

00:39:01.590 --> 00:39:03.920
dreaming than it does when you're focused.

00:39:03.920 --> 00:39:07.920
And that's because huge swaths of cortex are
communicating and interacting, you're mashing

00:39:07.920 --> 00:39:13.220
up new associations, you're exploring counter-factuals
and that's why people who daydream more score

00:39:13.220 --> 00:39:15.440
much higher on tests of creativity.

00:39:15.440 --> 00:39:17.820
So we now believe daydreaming is quite important.

00:39:17.820 --> 00:39:21.990
And being bored is a precursor to daydreaming,
right, you daydream, you fall down that rabbit

00:39:21.990 --> 00:39:24.970
hole in your own mind after you're a little
bit bored and so you entertain yourself.

00:39:24.970 --> 00:39:30.900
So I do worry, that in my own life, these,
you know, having these computers in our pockets

00:39:30.900 --> 00:39:34.100
does sometimes interfere with our ability
to go on these extended daydreams, that we're

00:39:34.100 --> 00:39:35.370
always interrupting them.

00:39:35.370 --> 00:39:40.110
So, you know, one way I've tried to compensate
for this is, you know, when I'm really stuck

00:39:40.110 --> 00:39:43.960
and stumped at work, I'll go for a walk and
just leave my phone behind.

00:39:43.960 --> 00:39:45.440
It makes me anxious for an hour
[Laughter]

00:39:45.440 --> 00:39:48.070
&gt;&gt;Jonah Lehrer: You know, to not be checking
email.

00:39:48.070 --> 00:39:49.401
But that's kind of how I've solved it.

00:39:49.401 --> 00:39:53.580
And I think it's, when you talk about technology
it's finding those kinds of tweaks.

00:39:53.580 --> 00:39:58.640
In general these tools are so wonderful and
I love them so much but just finding ways

00:39:58.640 --> 00:40:03.170
to kind of give ourselves a break from that
every once in a while.

00:40:03.170 --> 00:40:11.850
&gt;&gt;male #2: Hello, you mentioned that you shouldn't
brainstorm.

00:40:11.850 --> 00:40:16.360
I was kind of interested in that cause we
do an awful lot of that here.

00:40:16.360 --> 00:40:19.170
&gt;&gt;Jonah Lehrer: Yeah, this is classic brainstorming
I'm talking about.

00:40:19.170 --> 00:40:24.349
Classic brainstorming was invented by a guy
named Alex Osborn in the late 1940s.

00:40:24.349 --> 00:40:30.480
He's the O in BBDO; he's kind of the Don Draper,
the star of Mad Men, of his day, very swank,

00:40:30.480 --> 00:40:31.480
dapper fellow.

00:40:31.480 --> 00:40:35.230
In the series of best selling business books
he outlines this technique he called, he called

00:40:35.230 --> 00:40:36.230
brainstorming.

00:40:36.230 --> 00:40:39.370
There's really just one important rule to
brainstorming as he described it, which is

00:40:39.370 --> 00:40:40.990
no criticism is allowed.

00:40:40.990 --> 00:40:44.170
That all ideas are good ideas, right?

00:40:44.170 --> 00:40:48.900
The logic here is quite straight forward that
the imagination is meek and shy and fragile

00:40:48.900 --> 00:40:52.880
and if it's worried about being criticized
it'll just clam up and not be able to say

00:40:52.880 --> 00:40:55.090
anything interesting at all.

00:40:55.090 --> 00:40:56.800
And this is a feel good productivity technique,
right?

00:40:56.800 --> 00:41:01.940
We can all go into a room and free associate,
we fill the white board with our ideas, we

00:41:01.940 --> 00:41:06.060
all contributed to the group, we all felt
productive, no one had their feelings hurt,

00:41:06.060 --> 00:41:09.810
so there's a reason why people have done brainstorming
for so long.

00:41:09.810 --> 00:41:13.170
The only problem with brainstorming is that
it just doesn't work.

00:41:13.170 --> 00:41:18.440
That study after study over the last 60 years
has shown that people who brainstorm in a

00:41:18.440 --> 00:41:22.400
group come up with fewer ideas, and less original
ideas, than those same people who work on

00:41:22.400 --> 00:41:24.360
the problems by themselves.

00:41:24.360 --> 00:41:28.440
That we become less than some of our parts
when we brainstorm and the reason brainstorming

00:41:28.440 --> 00:41:31.870
doesn't work returns us to the very first
rule which is 'thou shall not criticize'.

00:41:31.870 --> 00:41:34.710
Cause it turns out that criticism is really
important.

00:41:34.710 --> 00:41:40.000
The work of Charlan Nemeth at UC Berkeley,
she's shown dozens of studies that groups

00:41:40.000 --> 00:41:44.590
that engage in debate and dissent, where they're
encouraged to constructively criticize the

00:41:44.590 --> 00:41:49.640
ideas of other people, they come up with anywhere
between 25 to 40 percent more ideas and those

00:41:49.640 --> 00:41:50.740
ideas are seen as more original.

00:41:50.740 --> 00:41:54.760
One of my favorite data points of hers is
that you ask people, you know, you have three

00:41:54.760 --> 00:41:59.450
different conditions, one condition is brainstorming,
one condition is do whatever the hell you

00:41:59.450 --> 00:42:01.770
want and third condition is debate and dissent.

00:42:01.770 --> 00:42:06.360
So you ask people to work on hard problems
like reduce traffic in the San Francisco Bay

00:42:06.360 --> 00:42:07.360
area.

00:42:07.360 --> 00:42:11.910
Then you let them work on the problem and
then you say, "Okay we're gonna bring you

00:42:11.910 --> 00:42:13.970
back in an hour or a day or a week."

00:42:13.970 --> 00:42:18.130
Give them some time and when you bring them
back you ask them, "Okay, since the study

00:42:18.130 --> 00:42:21.810
was over, have you had any more new ideas
since?"

00:42:21.810 --> 00:42:25.600
And it turns out that those who engaged in
debate and dissent come up with, on average,

00:42:25.600 --> 00:42:28.790
7 times more new ideas after the study is
over.

00:42:28.790 --> 00:42:33.800
They can't stop thinking about it cause they're
more engaged, invigorated, they're more surprised.

00:42:33.800 --> 00:42:38.791
That when we stick to our natural free associations,
when there is no debate and dissent, we kind

00:42:38.791 --> 00:42:42.970
of float on the superficial surface and it
turns out our free associations are pretty

00:42:42.970 --> 00:42:43.970
superficial.

00:42:43.970 --> 00:42:47.550
You know, over the last decade, psychologists
have amasses these word association charts

00:42:47.550 --> 00:42:51.090
and so I'm able to predict, with pretty good
accuracy, that if I ask you to free associate

00:42:51.090 --> 00:42:58.230
on blue, your first answer will be green,
followed by ocean, sky, jeans, Smurfs, maybe

00:42:58.230 --> 00:42:59.500
Miles Davis and so on.

00:42:59.500 --> 00:43:04.530
But nothing too interesting, I mean, I can
predict the vast majority of your free associations.

00:43:04.530 --> 00:43:07.880
That's because we're bound by language and
language is full of clichés.

00:43:07.880 --> 00:43:11.580
The way we get passed that superficial surface
is with criticism.

00:43:11.580 --> 00:43:15.840
That means we're fully engaged, we're digging
down deeper, we've got some skin in the game,

00:43:15.840 --> 00:43:19.720
so even after the meeting is over we keep
on thinking about it.

00:43:19.720 --> 00:43:24.730
So, we know brainstorming doesn't work, we've
got some hints as to improve it, to encourage

00:43:24.730 --> 00:43:28.960
debate and descent but, of course, research
comes with a huge caveat which is that all

00:43:28.960 --> 00:43:32.600
these studies are done with undergrads on
a one off basis.

00:43:32.600 --> 00:43:36.500
You give them an experiment, they come together
and they go away and they never see each other

00:43:36.500 --> 00:43:37.500
again.

00:43:37.500 --> 00:43:41.150
In a work place you're dealing with colleagues
who come together every single day.

00:43:41.150 --> 00:43:45.110
And it's unclear how to actually implement
debate and dissent.

00:43:45.110 --> 00:43:49.522
You see at Pixar where they're already struggling
with it, every day there begins with what

00:43:49.522 --> 00:43:50.550
they call the shredding meeting.

00:43:50.550 --> 00:43:53.980
Which is where they review the few seconds
of footage from the day before and they tear

00:43:53.980 --> 00:43:55.281
it apart, they dissect it.

00:43:55.281 --> 00:44:01.660
It sometimes, as Jobs put it, involves brutal
honesty but I'm not sure that would work for

00:44:01.660 --> 00:44:02.660
every place.

00:44:02.660 --> 00:44:07.870
So I think it's still unclear how to actually
translate debate and dissent to a collegial

00:44:07.870 --> 00:44:08.910
work environment.

00:44:08.910 --> 00:44:13.280
To make sure it's constructive, to make sure
it's, you know, remains positive and it remains

00:44:13.280 --> 00:44:14.280
productive.

00:44:14.280 --> 00:44:17.180
Cause the last thing you want, obviously,
is for people just going at it and getting

00:44:17.180 --> 00:44:19.330
personal and getting nasty.

00:44:19.330 --> 00:44:24.450
But what we can say now, I think with some
fairly good certainty, is that brainstorming

00:44:24.450 --> 00:44:25.450
just doesn't work.

00:44:25.450 --> 00:44:29.770
That it's time to find ways to experiment
with debate and dissent.

00:44:29.770 --> 00:44:36.070
&gt;&gt;female #1: Along the lines of inspiration,
could you tell the story of your favorite,

00:44:36.070 --> 00:44:41.230
how you came up with the idea of one of your
three books?

00:44:41.230 --> 00:44:47.500
&gt;&gt;Jonah Lehrer: Um, that's interesting, it
sounds so grandiose to talk about my own ideas

00:44:47.500 --> 00:44:51.760
in terms of epiphanies especially after having
just described "Like a Rolling Stone" that's

00:44:51.760 --> 00:44:54.560
quite intimidating.

00:44:54.560 --> 00:44:59.190
My first book really emerged from, I was working
in a neuroscience lab at the time and we were

00:44:59.190 --> 00:45:01.000
studying memory, the chemistry of memory.

00:45:01.000 --> 00:45:06.631
&gt;&gt;Jonah Lehrer: And basically what that meant
was you poke a sea slug over and over and

00:45:06.631 --> 00:45:09.180
over again until it gets bored by your touch.

00:45:09.180 --> 00:45:11.400
So it adapts, habituates, to the touch.

00:45:11.400 --> 00:45:14.870
And that's a form of memory and you can pull
out its neurons and figure out what, you know,

00:45:14.870 --> 00:45:18.410
the chemistry with a long term potentiation
is.

00:45:18.410 --> 00:45:22.000
Not most people think of it as a memory but
it was that kind of work.

00:45:22.000 --> 00:45:25.600
I mean very reductionist neuroscience.

00:45:25.600 --> 00:45:29.600
At the time, by sure accidents, I was taking
a course in French modernism.

00:45:29.600 --> 00:45:36.570
So, we were assigned Proust and I was reading
Swann's Way and his first volume of the epic

00:45:36.570 --> 00:45:39.070
and that's really a novel all about memory.

00:45:39.070 --> 00:45:42.290
It's all about long term storage of memories.

00:45:42.290 --> 00:45:49.320
I mean, it's this novelist who famously dips
his Madeleine, this buttery sea shell shaped

00:45:49.320 --> 00:45:53.330
cookie, into a lime floured tea and all of
a sudden he remembers all these memories from

00:45:53.330 --> 00:45:54.920
his childhood that he'd thought he forgot.

00:45:54.920 --> 00:45:59.550
And they all come flooding back to him triggered
by this scent of this childhood cookie.

00:45:59.550 --> 00:46:06.450
And so that got me thinking about here's this
novelist describing this very rich, very detailed

00:46:06.450 --> 00:46:12.540
memory and, in particular, how these memories
are triggered by the smell and taste of things.

00:46:12.540 --> 00:46:16.960
And at the time Proust had no idea how the
brain actually worked.

00:46:16.960 --> 00:46:21.120
There wasn't a whole lot of neuroanatomy and
yet, in the last decade, neuroscientists have

00:46:21.120 --> 00:46:25.660
come along and figured out that the reason
why, it's not called the Proust effect, why

00:46:25.660 --> 00:46:28.420
our smells and tastes are more sentimental.

00:46:28.420 --> 00:46:31.980
And that's because the olfactory cortex, the
part of the brain that processes smells and

00:46:31.980 --> 00:46:35.920
tastes, is the only sensory area directly
connected to the hippocampus, the center of

00:46:35.920 --> 00:46:36.920
long term memory.

00:46:36.920 --> 00:46:41.821
This is really an accident of evolution, it's
just cause for most primitive species, smell

00:46:41.821 --> 00:46:43.820
and taste are really, really important.

00:46:43.820 --> 00:46:46.770
We're more visual but this wire had never
been cut.

00:46:46.770 --> 00:46:51.400
And, so, even though Proust didn't know about
neuroanatomy, somehow he was able to intuit

00:46:51.400 --> 00:46:54.820
these wires and he was able to realize that,
yes, smell and taste are uniquely nostalgic.

00:46:54.820 --> 00:46:59.210
And so I was reading that literally in the
lab.

00:46:59.210 --> 00:47:04.040
And probably just because of where I was,
I was thinking about this novel and these

00:47:04.040 --> 00:47:07.820
silly scientific terms and that's where I
had the idea for my first book which is all

00:47:07.820 --> 00:47:14.160
about the intuitions of artists and how sometimes
they, they presage the discoveries in modern

00:47:14.160 --> 00:47:16.840
neuroscience.

00:47:16.840 --> 00:47:18.620
I wasn't in a shower or anything.

00:47:18.620 --> 00:47:20.730
[Laughter]
&gt;&gt;Jonah Lehrer: I was actually quite bored.

00:47:20.730 --> 00:47:24.990
I was waiting for an experiment that I'd been
trying to run for a month and it never worked

00:47:24.990 --> 00:47:28.200
and it turns out if actually never worked.

00:47:28.200 --> 00:47:30.720
And I kind of knew it would never actually
work so that's why I was passing the time

00:47:30.720 --> 00:47:34.340
in the lab reading a novel, so maybe my alpha
waves were going.

00:47:34.340 --> 00:47:36.420
But I don't know.

00:47:36.420 --> 00:47:42.000
Thanks for the question.

00:47:42.000 --> 00:47:47.380
&gt;&gt;male #2: Hello, I don't like the phrasing
of this question but I can't think of a better

00:47:47.380 --> 00:47:48.380
one.

00:47:48.380 --> 00:47:49.380
Can grit be learned?

00:47:49.380 --> 00:47:50.380
&gt;&gt;Jonah Lehrer: Yeah, I don't know.

00:47:50.380 --> 00:47:51.380
&gt;&gt;male #2: Can we teach it to our kids?

00:47:51.380 --> 00:47:54.580
Can we teach it to ourselves?

00:47:54.580 --> 00:47:59.970
&gt;&gt;Jonah Lehrer: Yeah, um, nobody knows for
sure, no one's on the detail genetic work

00:47:59.970 --> 00:48:05.260
to figure out the exact, you know, the exact
breakdown of heredity in terms of grit.

00:48:05.260 --> 00:48:10.500
The presumption is that like just about every
other personality trait it's about 50/50.

00:48:10.500 --> 00:48:13.100
50 percent nature, 50 percent nurture.

00:48:13.100 --> 00:48:14.550
And that's good news, right?

00:48:14.550 --> 00:48:17.480
Cause that means you can really shift the
curve.

00:48:17.480 --> 00:48:22.040
The question, of course, is how then to shift
the curve, how actually teach grit.

00:48:22.040 --> 00:48:27.780
Duckworth is just beginning a ten year longitudinal
study where she looks at students in the Philadelphia

00:48:27.780 --> 00:48:32.280
District schools, public schools in the inner
city of Philadelphia and these are some sad

00:48:32.280 --> 00:48:36.520
statistics, but 45 percent of these kids drop
out before graduation.

00:48:36.520 --> 00:48:40.160
She's focusing on the 55 percent of kids who
stay in, who already show higher levels of

00:48:40.160 --> 00:48:41.730
grit than those who drop out.

00:48:41.730 --> 00:48:47.430
Of those 55 percent who stay in, 95 percent
that the longer they stay in school the worse

00:48:47.430 --> 00:48:52.470
their test scores get, the farther they fall
behind their peers in Pennsylvania.

00:48:52.470 --> 00:48:54.820
This is just, to me, depressed the hell out
of me, right?

00:48:54.820 --> 00:48:58.150
The longer they are in these schools, the
worse they get.

00:48:58.150 --> 00:49:02.400
5 percent of these kids, though, in these
same schools, in the same struggling community,

00:49:02.400 --> 00:49:04.900
with little household support, they make themselves
better.

00:49:04.900 --> 00:49:06.740
They find a way to improve their test scores.

00:49:06.740 --> 00:49:09.990
So Duckworth is trying to figure out what
sets these kids apart.

00:49:09.990 --> 00:49:12.970
Sure enough they score off the charts in grit
but she wants to figure out how does that

00:49:12.970 --> 00:49:13.970
cash out?

00:49:13.970 --> 00:49:14.970
What does that actually mean?

00:49:14.970 --> 00:49:17.810
She's looking at their work habits, their
routines and so on.

00:49:17.810 --> 00:49:19.510
She's pulled out some interesting stuff.

00:49:19.510 --> 00:49:21.620
They tend to focus on exemplars when they're
frustrated.

00:49:21.620 --> 00:49:25.660
So they've got a model, maybe it's a sports
star, maybe it's Martin Luther King, someone

00:49:25.660 --> 00:49:30.680
like that who they know persevered through
difficulty and they think about them a lot,

00:49:30.680 --> 00:49:32.510
especially when they're going through a tough
time.

00:49:32.510 --> 00:49:37.260
So, one of the first pieces of advice is give
kids heroes, give them exemplars.

00:49:37.260 --> 00:49:41.850
She also found some interesting stuff like
this one I didn't expect, these kids from

00:49:41.850 --> 00:49:46.260
a certain perspective are just more thoughtless
that when they're doing their algebra homework

00:49:46.260 --> 00:49:50.360
they're not thinking about the ball game on
TV, they're not taking the opportunity cost

00:49:50.360 --> 00:49:53.100
of their activity, they just do the algebra
homework cause that's what they need to do.

00:49:53.100 --> 00:49:56.990
So they're not exploring counterfactuals,
what else they could be doing, they're just

00:49:56.990 --> 00:49:57.990
doing it.

00:49:57.990 --> 00:50:01.770
So they think less about alternatives which
is kind of interesting.

00:50:01.770 --> 00:50:04.690
They're more focused on tangible progress
than the long term goal.

00:50:04.690 --> 00:50:08.950
Cause that goal is so distant that if you're
just thinking about the long term goal you'll

00:50:08.950 --> 00:50:10.470
get demotivated very quickly.

00:50:10.470 --> 00:50:12.520
So it's very important to think about, "Well,
I got better today.

00:50:12.520 --> 00:50:14.580
I'm doing a little bit better today than I
was yesterday."

00:50:14.580 --> 00:50:16.040
And so on.

00:50:16.040 --> 00:50:20.990
But it's too early to say, I think, that these
are the 5 things you need to do to build grit

00:50:20.990 --> 00:50:23.260
up in yourself or in your children.

00:50:23.260 --> 00:50:29.740
Right now Duckworth's best advice is this
wonderful maxim she refers to, choose easy,

00:50:29.740 --> 00:50:35.250
work hard, which means that we should expose
our kids and ourselves to a menu of possibilities.

00:50:35.250 --> 00:50:37.960
To a lot of things you might fall in love
with.

00:50:37.960 --> 00:50:42.680
Maybe it's painting, maybe it's drawing, maybe
it's computer programming, maybe it's marketing,

00:50:42.680 --> 00:50:46.320
who knows, just let yourself find something
that feels like fun, that feels like play

00:50:46.320 --> 00:50:47.320
not like work.

00:50:47.320 --> 00:50:52.130
And then once you commit to it, you have to
remind yourself every single day to work hard.

00:50:52.130 --> 00:50:57.060
To put in your ten thousand hours plus or
minus five thousand hours, that it's not always

00:50:57.060 --> 00:50:59.660
gonna be fun, in fact, it'll rarely be fun.

00:50:59.660 --> 00:51:04.780
People who are really gritty, they find the
un-fun stuff just as aversive as people who

00:51:04.780 --> 00:51:07.190
don't have grit, it's just they're able to
push on through it.

00:51:07.190 --> 00:51:10.840
So, choose easy, work hard is, I think, the
best advice we have right now.

00:51:10.840 --> 00:51:17.180
