00:51:48.900 --> 00:51:57.100
&gt;&gt;male #4: Hi, um, you mentioned scientists
going from working individually to working

00:51:57.100 --> 00:51:59.960
in larger and progressively larger groups.

00:51:59.960 --> 00:52:07.601
And you mentioned some of the scientists working
individually, Darwin and Einstein and they

00:52:07.601 --> 00:52:10.410
had very revolutionary ideas.

00:52:10.410 --> 00:52:19.060
I'm wondering if the move to groups will lead
to more evolutionary science as opposed to

00:52:19.060 --> 00:52:30.620
revolutionary science where if the ideas of
energy as matter would get thrown out in a

00:52:30.620 --> 00:52:32.750
debate early on in a group?

00:52:32.750 --> 00:52:36.400
&gt;&gt;Jonah Lehrer: It's a really interesting
question and it's something I've talked with

00:52:36.400 --> 00:52:37.530
Jones about extensively.

00:52:37.530 --> 00:52:42.860
And I think it's unclear to him whether or
not, I think, I feel like physics if it's

00:52:42.860 --> 00:52:47.350
just too immature to still have those kinds
of total paradigm shifts or if we now know

00:52:47.350 --> 00:52:51.400
enough about the structure of reality where
it's just become an evolutionary science.

00:52:51.400 --> 00:52:52.400
Yes?

00:52:52.400 --> 00:52:55.200
&gt;&gt;male #4: The same was thought before Einstein

00:52:55.200 --> 00:52:56.440
&gt;&gt;Jonah Lehrer: Of course, in 1903

00:52:56.440 --> 00:52:58.900
&gt;&gt;male #4: They've become a scientist, we
know everything.

00:52:58.900 --> 00:53:06.530
&gt;&gt;Jonah Lehrer: Of course, they've been saying
that, I'm sure Pythagoras was complaining

00:53:06.530 --> 00:53:09.040
about, ugh, all the interesting problems have
been solved.

00:53:09.040 --> 00:53:12.050
[Laughter]
&gt;&gt;Jonah Lehrer: It's a refrain you see again

00:53:12.050 --> 00:53:14.640
and again but eventually it's gonna be true,
right?

00:53:14.640 --> 00:53:19.190
Eventually we will have a good enough map
of reality where, you know, our predictions

00:53:19.190 --> 00:53:20.400
line up.

00:53:20.400 --> 00:53:26.500
And, you know, I think it's unclear with all
these super colliders coming out online, if,

00:53:26.500 --> 00:53:28.900
you know how much they'll change about our
assumptions.

00:53:28.900 --> 00:53:32.890
So, I think there are many, many interesting
problems to solve in a field like physics,

00:53:32.890 --> 00:53:36.600
in a field like neuroscience, the answers
even more clear that we know nothing.

00:53:36.600 --> 00:53:40.690
That right now we know enough just to know
how little we actually understand.

00:53:40.690 --> 00:53:44.600
Um, so I think there's absolutely revolutions
waiting to happen.

00:53:44.600 --> 00:53:51.840
I don't think, necessarily, that teams, by
definition, will make those paradigm shifts

00:53:51.840 --> 00:53:52.840
less radical.

00:53:52.840 --> 00:53:56.210
I mean, I think that's our old model of big
paradigm shifts come from individuals.

00:53:56.210 --> 00:53:59.670
I think Jones would argue it's just now we
need to be more interdisciplinary.

00:53:59.670 --> 00:54:04.560
When you look at a field like neuroscience,
which I know better that physics, unfortunately,

00:54:04.560 --> 00:54:09.240
and you look at the kinds of problems we need
to solve, they require people with backgrounds

00:54:09.240 --> 00:54:13.550
in, you know, like the Connectum, it's a big
movement neuroscience to understand the actual

00:54:13.550 --> 00:54:14.840
wiring diagram of the brain.

00:54:14.840 --> 00:54:20.340
That requires people with backgrounds in computer
science, computer programming, you know, molecular

00:54:20.340 --> 00:54:24.690
biology, neuroscience, neurology, I mean,
it requires all these different people to

00:54:24.690 --> 00:54:25.690
come together.

00:54:25.690 --> 00:54:29.420
No single field, no single discipline can
solve it by themselves.

00:54:29.420 --> 00:54:34.170
And what Jones argues is there simply are
limits to how much knowledge the brain can

00:54:34.170 --> 00:54:35.170
hold.

00:54:35.170 --> 00:54:39.869
It takes ten years to even amass an expertise
in one of those disciplines.

00:54:39.869 --> 00:54:43.040
We don't live long enough to become an expert
in enough disciplines to actually tackle these

00:54:43.040 --> 00:54:47.040
very, very hard problems which is why they
exceed our individual capabilities.

00:54:47.040 --> 00:54:49.160
But it's an interesting question.

00:54:49.160 --> 00:54:51.050
I think there's no good answer for it yet.

00:54:51.050 --> 00:54:56.820
I think we'll have to see how 21st century
science plays out.

