00:55:20.960 --> 00:55:25.040
&gt;&gt;Jonah Lehrer: It's interesting, I mean,
a lot of people, it turns out physical activity

00:55:25.040 --> 00:55:28.820
when it comes to like daydreaming and alpha
waves whether or not it's relaxing, it's very

00:55:28.820 --> 00:55:29.820
divisive.

00:55:29.820 --> 00:55:33.240
Some people, and people in these studies,
some people find going to the gym very relaxing.

00:55:33.240 --> 00:55:36.900
They find the Stairmaster or the Treadmill
or jogging outside, very relaxing.

00:55:36.900 --> 00:55:39.580
They'll talk about all the great ideas they
have when they jog.

00:55:39.580 --> 00:55:41.210
Some people find it very stressful.

00:55:41.210 --> 00:55:45.720
So that's why it's tough, in general, to come
up with a universal prescription for how to

00:55:45.720 --> 00:55:47.260
relax yourself.

00:55:47.260 --> 00:55:50.960
Maybe it's playing football, maybe it's playing
foosball.

00:55:50.960 --> 00:55:54.620
It's different for everybody and that's why
it's so important for each individual to seek

00:55:54.620 --> 00:55:57.619
out their own place that puts them at ease.

00:55:57.619 --> 00:56:02.710
I mean, on the larger subject of physical
exertion, it's so essential.

00:56:02.710 --> 00:56:07.680
And I think it's been one of the big themes
in modern neuroscience, which has surprised

00:56:07.680 --> 00:56:11.780
neuroscience, cause I think for a long time
we like to flatter ourselves by thinking about

00:56:11.780 --> 00:56:16.570
the brain as somehow separate from the body,
you know, just, we're just this, you know,

00:56:16.570 --> 00:56:23.130
ethereal brain in a vat, mostly un tethered
and disconnected from this fleshly machine

00:56:23.130 --> 00:56:24.370
we gotta carry around.

00:56:24.370 --> 00:56:26.150
Well, it turns out that's not true at all.

00:56:26.150 --> 00:56:31.170
That's why neurogenesis, for instance, the
birth of new brain cells in, you know, even

00:56:31.170 --> 00:56:34.170
the adult brain, is very closely connected
with physical exercise.

00:56:34.170 --> 00:56:38.020
The single best way to increase neurogenesis
is to get more exercise, to move about more.

00:56:38.020 --> 00:56:40.990
You see this is rodents and you see this in
humans.

00:56:40.990 --> 00:56:45.130
Nobody knows why that is but we know it's
just, it's important.

00:56:45.130 --> 00:56:49.700
Some new studies have come out looking at
dementia and blood flow and simply blood flow

00:56:49.700 --> 00:56:52.300
to the brain increases with exercise.

00:56:52.300 --> 00:56:56.230
It's improving your cardiovascular system
and so one of the best ways to save off dementia

00:56:56.230 --> 00:57:01.140
seems to be even better than playing bridge
every day which used to be like the best prescription,

00:57:01.140 --> 00:57:06.300
is going for a walk, getting exercise, getting
your blood going.

00:57:06.300 --> 00:57:09.050
Now one of the control studies, which I'm
kind of fascinated to see how it turns out,

00:57:09.050 --> 00:57:11.630
there compared exercise to people that do
headstands.

00:57:11.630 --> 00:57:15.500
Cause if it's just about blood flow, right,
then a headstand should work pretty well.

00:57:15.500 --> 00:57:17.530
[Laughter]
&gt;&gt;Jonah Lehrer: So that'll be interesting,

00:57:17.530 --> 00:57:19.960
that'll be a better test to the causality.

00:57:19.960 --> 00:57:23.490
So, I think that's due to come out next year.

00:57:23.490 --> 00:57:28.550
Um, I mean, right now we can say it's important,
I don't think we understand all the causal

00:57:28.550 --> 00:57:31.370
mechanisms, that's my release on the research.

00:57:31.370 --> 00:57:35.760
&gt;&gt;female #2: I think we're about running out
of time but if we could just do two more questions.

00:57:35.760 --> 00:57:39.150
I've got one from Daniel in the Soho office.

00:57:39.150 --> 00:57:43.400
You talked about idle conversation in the
online space and gave the example of Skype.

00:57:43.400 --> 00:57:48.740
What's your perspective on the rise of social
and catalyzing serendipitous connections and

00:57:48.740 --> 00:57:52.150
is there any way of transferring serendipity
into the online space?

00:57:52.150 --> 00:57:53.850
&gt;&gt;Jonah Lehrer: I have no doubt there is.

00:57:53.850 --> 00:57:58.740
I'd be the last person to ever bet against
the future innovations of tech companies.

00:57:58.740 --> 00:58:02.190
I think it's astonishing how far we've come
in a short amount of time.

00:58:02.190 --> 00:58:05.650
That's, I don't think we've found it yet.

00:58:05.650 --> 00:58:09.730
I think too often the online space, our interactions,
and this is at least true with my interactions,

00:58:09.730 --> 00:58:12.869
they're driven by what psychologists call
self-similarity principle.

00:58:12.869 --> 00:58:17.510
Where even a platform like Twitter, which
I think could be used to foster some kind

00:58:17.510 --> 00:58:18.510
of serendipity.

00:58:18.510 --> 00:58:22.770
And I'm always depressed when I look at who
I follow on Twitter, it's people a lot like

00:58:22.770 --> 00:58:28.110
me, people who are interested in the brain,
interested in science, people who are good

00:58:28.110 --> 00:58:31.020
liberals, etcetera, etcetera.

00:58:31.020 --> 00:58:32.940
And this is the self similarity principle.

00:58:32.940 --> 00:58:36.900
This has been found in study after study that
it's always easier to spend time with people

00:58:36.900 --> 00:58:38.370
who are just like us.

00:58:38.370 --> 00:58:42.150
And so, when given a choice, we seek out those
who think like us, who talk like us, vote

00:58:42.150 --> 00:58:46.050
for the same politicians, speak the same languages,
use the same acronyms and so on.

00:58:46.050 --> 00:58:48.830
That's more comfortable, that's easier, less
tension.

00:58:48.830 --> 00:58:52.690
And I think that speaks to the importance
of what cities do.

00:58:52.690 --> 00:58:55.270
Cities bring together a bunch of weirdos and
throw us together.

00:58:55.270 --> 00:58:58.030
We can't choose who we bump into.

00:58:58.030 --> 00:59:04.310
And so, in a sense, I think that when you
imagine a serendipitous online space, it would

00:59:04.310 --> 00:59:05.310
be kind of unpleasant.

00:59:05.310 --> 00:59:08.810
It's hard to imagine how you would have serendipity.

00:59:08.810 --> 00:59:12.180
You know, have that human friction but not
have it be so unpleasant.

00:59:12.180 --> 00:59:19.030
Have us choose to go to a website that's gonna
say, "I'm gonna confront you with strangers

00:59:19.030 --> 00:59:20.160
who think differently than you."

00:59:20.160 --> 00:59:25.130
I have no doubt it'll happen cause I think
it's a really important next step, but I have

00:59:25.130 --> 00:59:30.030
yet to come up with a good plan of how to
make it happen other than to randomly choose

00:59:30.030 --> 00:59:32.870
people to follow on Twitter.

00:59:32.870 --> 00:59:36.770
But I have no doubt that someday a company
like Google will come up with a way to actually

00:59:36.770 --> 00:59:40.460
foster serendipity online, interpersonal serendipity
especially.

00:59:40.460 --> 00:59:48.690
&gt;&gt; male off mic: the last one
&gt;&gt;female #4: Hi, very fascinating speech,

00:59:48.690 --> 00:59:53.470
I've got a real interest in the grit thresholds
neurologically.

00:59:53.470 --> 00:59:58.730
I'm wondering if any studies have been taken
by people with respect to, you know, these

00:59:58.730 --> 01:00:04.640
highly focused, highly successful creative
people who have a very high level of grit

01:00:04.640 --> 01:00:09.010
and those that also have a very high level
grit that like certain sports stars and other

01:00:09.010 --> 01:00:13.650
people who get to that, you know, high level
of grit and then get, you know, what is characterized

01:00:13.650 --> 01:00:17.380
as burn out, ME or chronic fatigue those sorts
of things.

01:00:17.380 --> 01:00:20.710
How do you think that works, you know, neurologically
in the brain?

01:00:20.710 --> 01:00:23.000
What differentiates between those two types
of people?

01:00:23.000 --> 01:00:26.511
&gt;&gt;Jonah Lehrer: You mean what separates those
with lots of grit from those who?

01:00:26.511 --> 01:00:30.600
&gt;&gt;female #4: Who had lots of grit but then
the grit threshold is obviously too high and

01:00:30.600 --> 01:00:33.350
then the brain goes, "I can't take this anymore"
and shuts down.

01:00:33.350 --> 01:00:34.670
&gt;&gt;Jonah Lehrer: I mean it's a great question.

01:00:34.670 --> 01:00:37.930
There's no, no one is really taking grit to
the brain yet.

01:00:37.930 --> 01:00:41.730
It's a brand new character trait, at least
in the context of character traits it's only

01:00:41.730 --> 01:00:42.970
been around since 2005.

01:00:42.970 --> 01:00:47.060
So, you know, we've got some sense of what
underlies it from lots of work on self control

01:00:47.060 --> 01:00:49.830
cause grits in the self control family.

01:00:49.830 --> 01:00:55.200
But it's too soon to say what exactly parts
of the brain fizzles out or kind of goes limp

01:00:55.200 --> 01:01:00.960
when people, who clearly were able to put
in the work, just give up.

01:01:00.960 --> 01:01:06.290
It's also important to point out that it's
not always great to just have endless grit

01:01:06.290 --> 01:01:10.200
resources that, grit, like all character traits,
you can have too much of it.

01:01:10.200 --> 01:01:13.890
So you get increasing returns, it gets better
and better and at a certain point you can

01:01:13.890 --> 01:01:16.330
have too much grit, right, you can be too
single minded.

01:01:16.330 --> 01:01:20.390
Like, I may wanna be a professional basketball
player, in fact, I do wanna be a professional

01:01:20.390 --> 01:01:21.820
basketball player.

01:01:21.820 --> 01:01:25.390
But someone's gotta pull me aside and say,
"You know what, even if you're the greatest

01:01:25.390 --> 01:01:27.119
person in the world, look at yourself.

01:01:27.119 --> 01:01:28.119
You still won't get there."

01:01:28.119 --> 01:01:32.369
[Laughter]
&gt;&gt;Jonah Lehrer: So if I'm too gritty, I may

01:01:32.369 --> 01:01:35.360
devote my life to trying to accomplish an
impossible goal.

01:01:35.360 --> 01:01:39.280
So grit is also about being a little strategic
about saying like what are the goals that

01:01:39.280 --> 01:01:42.080
are worth pursuing given who I am?

01:01:42.080 --> 01:01:45.010
That's why Duckworth argues we have to be
more realistic in talking to our kids.

01:01:45.010 --> 01:01:48.570
Like, right now we say, "If you can dream
it, you can do it!

01:01:48.570 --> 01:01:49.600
Just go for it!"

01:01:49.600 --> 01:01:51.550
When, maybe that's kind of bad advice sometimes.

01:01:51.550 --> 01:01:53.920
Maybe we should make sure that, I know it
sounds sad, right?

01:01:53.920 --> 01:01:57.380
[Laughter]
&gt;&gt;Jonah Lehrer: It sounds so cynical but let's

01:01:57.380 --> 01:01:58.720
be honest.

01:01:58.720 --> 01:02:03.220
We can't all play in the NBA and that's just
the fact of life.

01:02:03.220 --> 01:02:07.550
So we should make sure our kids, at the very
least, have some kind of tangible plan for

01:02:07.550 --> 01:02:10.590
getting from, you know, where they are to
where they wanna be.

01:02:10.590 --> 01:02:14.080
And maybe it'll mean just giving them better
advice at an early age.

01:02:14.080 --> 01:02:16.900
And make sure they've got realistic goals
too.

01:02:16.900 --> 01:02:21.010
Not that we shouldn't dream or anything, I
should be the last person to suggest that,

01:02:21.010 --> 01:02:22.900
but that we should be realistic.

01:02:22.900 --> 01:02:30.070
So, you know, in terms of why some people
give up, um, I think it's often that, one

01:02:30.070 --> 01:02:33.310
explanation that I might propose is that these
are people that are actually very strategic

01:02:33.310 --> 01:02:34.359
about goal setting.

01:02:34.359 --> 01:02:38.880
Maybe they were a football star and they had
a lot of grit and they put in those ten thousand

01:02:38.880 --> 01:02:43.280
hours and got really good at it but then they
realized that I'm just, you know, my talents

01:02:43.280 --> 01:02:48.330
are fading, I'm not quite good enough, I should
find a new goal while I still can and devote

01:02:48.330 --> 01:02:51.930
my grit to that resource.

01:02:51.930 --> 01:02:55.980
One of the important things about grit is
the limited resource, it's a scarce resource.

01:02:55.980 --> 01:02:58.950
So, it's a bit like self control, you have
to figure out how to allocate it depending

01:02:58.950 --> 01:03:00.430
on what you wanna do.

01:03:00.430 --> 01:03:04.030
So, sometimes you see people switching, a
lot of gritty people will have just one goal

01:03:04.030 --> 01:03:08.670
for their entire life and do that, they're
able to pivot but once they pivot they're

01:03:08.670 --> 01:03:11.980
able to commit to that goal.

01:03:11.980 --> 01:03:17.030
So grit isn't just about stupid persistence
it's also about being strategic in how you're

01:03:17.030 --> 01:03:18.030
single minded.

